<p>
  There are a lot of definitions to keep track of in graph theory.  Here is a glossary of the terms we have already used and will soon encounter.
</p>

	<assemblage>
		<title>Graph Theory Definitions</title>
		<p>
			<dl width="medium">
				<li>
					<title>Graph</title>
					<p><index><main>graph</main></index> A collection of
						<term>vertices</term>, some of which are connected by
						<term>edges</term>. More precisely, a pair of sets <m>V</m> and <m>E</m> where <m>V</m> is a set of vertices and <m>E</m> is a set of 2-element subsets of <m>V</m>.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Adjacent</title>
					<p><index><main>adjacent</main></index> Two vertices are
						<term>adjacent</term> if they are connected by an edge. Two edges are
						<term>adjacent</term> if they share a vertex.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Bipartite graph</title>
					<p><index><main>bipartite</main></index> A graph for which it is possible to divide the vertices into two disjoint sets such that there are no edges between any two vertices in the same set.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Complete bipartite graph</title>
					<p>A bipartite graph for which every vertex in the first set is adjacent to every vertex in the second set.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Complete graph</title>
					<p><index><main>complete graph</main></index> A graph in which every pair of vertices is adjacent.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Connected</title>
					<p><index><main>connected</main></index> A graph is
						<term>connected</term> if there is a path from any vertex to any other vertex.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Chromatic number</title>
					<p><index><main>chromatic number</main></index> The minimum number of colors required in a proper vertex coloring of the graph.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Cycle</title>
					<p><index><main>cycle</main></index> A path (see below) that starts and stops at the same vertex, but contains no other repeated vertices.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Degree of a vertex</title>
					<p><index><main>degree</main></index> The number of edges incident to a vertex.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Euler path</title>
					<p>A walk which uses each edge exactly once.
					</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Euler circuit</title>
					<p><index><main>Euler path</main></index> An Euler path which starts and stops at the same vertex.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Multigraph</title>
					<p><index><main>multigraph</main></index> A
						<term>multigraph</term> is just like a graph but can contain multiple edges between two vertices as well as single edge loops (that is an edge from a vertex to itself).</p>
				</li>


				<li>
					<title>Planar</title>
					<p><index><main>planar</main></index> A graph which can be drawn (in the plane) without any edges crossing.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Subgraph</title>
					<p><index><main>subgraph</main></index> We say that <m>H</m> is a
						<term>subgraph</term> of <m>G</m> if every vertex and edge of <m>H</m> is also a vertex or edge of <m>G</m>. We say <m>H</m> is an
						<term>induced</term> subgraph of <m>G</m> if every vertex of <m>H</m> is a vertex of <m>G</m> and each pair of vertices in <m>H</m> are adjacent in <m>H</m> if and only if they are adjacent in <m>G</m>.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Tree</title>
					<p><index><main>tree</main></index> A (connected) graph with no cycles. (A non-connected graph with no cycles is called a
						<term>forest</term>.) The vertices in a tree with degree 1 are called
						<term>leaves</term>.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Vertex coloring</title>
					<p><index><main>vertex coloring</main></index> An assignment of colors to each of the vertices of a graph. A vertex coloring is
						<term>proper</term> if adjacent vertices are always colored differently.</p>
				</li>

				<li>
					<title>Walk</title>
					<p><index><main>walk</main></index> A sequence of vertices such that consecutive vertices (in the sequence) are adjacent (in the graph). A walk in which no vertex is repeated is called
						<term>simple</term>.</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>
	</assemblage>


	<exercises>
		<title>Exercises for Section 4.1</title>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If 10 people each shake hands with each other, how many handshakes took place? What does this question have to do with graph theory?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					This is asking for the number of edges in <m>K_{10}</m>. Each vertex (person) has degree (shook hands with) 9 (people). So the sum of the degrees is <m>90</m>. However, the degrees count each edge (handshake) twice, so there are 45 edges in the graph. That is how many handshakes took place.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Among a group of 5 people, is it possible for everyone to be friends with exactly 2 of the people in the group? What about 3 of the people in the group?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					It is possible for everyone to be friends with exactly 2 people. You could arrange the 5 people in a circle and say that everyone is friends with the two people on either side of them (so you get the graph <m>C_5</m>). However, it is not possible for everyone to be friends with 3 people. That would lead to a graph with an odd number of odd degree vertices which is impossible since the sum of the degrees must be even.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

